SIMPLE: muster
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Muster
<hw>Mus"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>moustre</ets>, OF. <ets>mostre</ets>, <ets>moustre</ets>, F.
<ets>montre</ets>, LL. <ets>monstra</ets>. See <er>Muster</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something shown for imitation; a
pattern.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A show; a display.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Piers Plowman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An assembling or review of troops, as for parade,
verification of numbers, inspection, exercise, or introduction into
service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hurried <qex>muster</qex> of the soldiers of liberty.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See how in warlike <qex>muster</qex> they appear,⟦br⟧
In rhombs, and wedges, and half-moons, and wings.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The sum total of an army when assembled for review
and inspection; the whole number of effective men in an army.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the <qex>muster</qex> was thirty thousands of men.</q>
<rj><qau>Wyclif.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye publish the <qex>musters</qex> of your own bands, and proclaim
them to amount of thousands.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Any assemblage or display; a gathering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of the temporal grandees of the realm, mentof their wives and
daughters, the <qex>muster</qex> was great and splendid.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muster book</b></col>, <cd>a book in which military
forces are registered.</cd> -- <col><b>Muster file</b></col>, <cd>a
muster roll.</cd> -- <col><b>Muster master</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>,
<cd>one who takes an account of troops, and of their equipment; a
mustering officer; an inspector.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> --
<col><b>Muster roll</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a list or register
of all the men in a company, troop, or regiment, present or accounted
for on the day of muster.</cd> -- <col><b>To pass muster</b></col>,
<cd>to pass through a muster or inspection without
censure.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such excuses will not <qex>pass muster</qex> with God.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muster</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Muster
<hw>Mus"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mustered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mustering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mustren</ets>, prop.,
to show, OF. <ets>mostrer</ets>, <ets>mustrer</ets>,
<ets>moustrer</ets>, <ets>monstrer</ets>, F. <ets>montrer</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>monstrare</ets> to show. See <er>Monster</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To collect and display; to assemble, as troops for parade,
inspection, exercise, or the like.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: To summon together; to enroll in service; to
get together.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Mustering <xex>all its force</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the gay feathers he could <qex>muster</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To muster troops into service</b></col>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to inspect and enter troops on the muster roll of
the army.</cd> -- <col><b>To muster troops out of service</b></col>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to register them for final payment and
discharge.</cd> -- <col><b>To muster up</b></col>, <cd>to gather up; to
succeed in obtaining; to obtain with some effort or
difficulty.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One of those who can <qex>muster up</qex> sufficient sprightliness
to engage in a game of forfeits.</q> <rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muster</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Muster
<hw>Mus"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be gathered together for
parade, inspection, exercise, or the like; to come together as parts of
a force or body; <as>as, his supporters <ex>mustered</ex> in
force</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>mustering</xex> squadron.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mustily</ent>⟦br⟧
